  <item>
    <title>Neighborhood network builders: a summary</title>
    <link>http://commotionwireless.net/fr/blog/neighborhood-network-builders-summary</link>
    <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot; property=&quot;content:encoded&quot;&gt; &lt;p&gt;As part of our research for the Commotion Human Interface Guidelines, we interviewed four people who have been involved in building community wireless networks around Detroit (see earlier blog posts for excerpts). Based on these interviews and our experience working with various users, we recommend that Commotion developers and organizers implement the following concepts:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Building successful software&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Our interviews confirmed that users expect long-term reliability, speed, and ease of use when using wireless devices. The Commotion user interface should:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Walk a user through the setup process.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Work well across platforms, browsers, and devices.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Be as fast as using a non-mesh WiFi access point.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Help users understand mesh network security.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Allow for easy monitoring of network status in terms that users can understand.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Offer troubleshooting suggestions when a network does not work correctly.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
     <pubDate>Tue, 08 May 2012 19:51:27 +0000</pubDate>
 <dc:creator>The Work Department</dc:creator>
